

                                 VOIDSTEP


OVERVIEW
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
VoidStep is a lightweight, low-level process tracer and debugger built from 
scratch in C. It leverages the Linux ptrace(2) system call to intercept and 
control child processes at the instruction level.

The project was designed to demonstrate core concepts of systems programming,
including signal handling, register manipulation, and memory patching.


INSTALLATION
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
VoidStep uses the standard GNU build system. To compile and install:

    $ ./configure
    $ make
    # make install (optional)

QUICK START
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
1. Compile your target program without PIE for absolute addressing:
    $ gcc -no-pie -g -o target target.c

2. Find the entry point or a function address:
    $ nm target | grep main

3. Launch VoidStep with the target and the breakpoint address:
    $ ./voidstep ./target 0x40114d

COMMANDS
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Once a breakpoint is hit, you can use the following commands:
  (s)tep     - Execute the next machine instruction.
  (c)ontinue - Resume process execution until the next trap or exit.
  (x)examine - Read 8 bytes of memory at a specific address.
  (w)rite    - Overwrite memory at a specific address with new data.
